Details_1: State of Emergency. Governor Ned Lamont declared both a public health emergency and a civil preparedness emergency. These declarations allowed to restrict travel, close public schools, and buildings.

More restrictions. Prohibition of social and recreational gatherings to 250 people; Limits on nursing home visitors; Extension of DMV licensing renewal deadlines and suspension of other DMV requirements
More restrictions. Suspension of in-person open meeting requirements; Waiver of manufacturer registration requirement for hand sanitizer

Schools. Cancellation of classes at all public schools; Flexibility of graduation requirements and prescribed courses of study.
Healthcare. COVID-19 information sharing between facilities that treat persons with psychiatric disabilities, DPH, and local health directors.

More restrictions. Reduction of social and recreational gatherings to 50 people; Limits restaurant, bar, and private club operations to off-premise consumption of food and non-alcoholic beverages;
Closure of off-track betting facility operations;Closure of gym, sports, fitness, recreation facilities, and movie theaters

More closures. Closure of large, indoor shopping malls; Closure of places of public amusement.
Healthcare. Expansion of Medicaid telehealth coverage to audio-only telephone
Election. Postponement of presidential primary to June 2.
"Stay Safe, Stay Home" restrictions on all workplaces for non-essential business.
Schools. Extension of class cancellations at all public schools to April 20

More restrictions. Further reduction of social and recreational gatherings to 5 people; Further restrictions on retail operations; Suspension of 21-month limit on Temporary Family Assistance; Suspension of school testing assessments for 2019-20 school year.
Recreation. Restrictions on entrance to state parks, forests, and other lands; Curbside pickup of alcoholic beverages permitted

Healthcare. Protection from civil liability for actions or omissions in support of the state’s COVID-19 response; Financial protections for the uninsured and people covered by insurance who receive out-of-network health care services during the public health emergency.
Healthcare. Temporary permits for certain health care providers extended and fees waived

Renters. Protections for residential renters impacted by COVID-19.
Schools. Continued cancellation of school classes through May 20, 2020; Extension of closures, distancing, and safety measures through May 20, 2020.
Healthcare. Implementation of a nursing home surge plan
Healthcare. Approval of temporary additional nursing home beds for COVID-19 recovery
Masks. Cloth face coverings or higher level of protection required in public wherever close contact is unavoidable

Healthcare. Additions to the definition of telehealth provider; Additions to permissible out-of-state healthcare providers; Temporary suspension of physician assistant supervision restrictions; Temporary suspension of in-person supervision requirement for advanced practice registered nurses; Provision of services by respiratory care therapist and respiratory care technician students

Healthcare. Mandatory reporting by managed residential communities; Mandatory reporting by nursing homes; Civil Penalties for failure to comply with mandatory reporting; Waiving certain Medicaid prior authorization requirements; Waiving requirements for signed delivery receipt for medical equipment, devices, and supplies.
Healthcare. Additional flexibility for Medicaid-enrolled providers to perform telehealth through audio-only methods for new patients
Relief Funds. Eligible residents started receiving $600 Unemploymnet benefits.
Access to Food. Authority to waive certain requirements for the issuance of vouchers under the Farmers’ Market Nutrition Program for Women, Infants, and Children
Healthcare. Pharmacists are permitted to order and administer Food and Drug Administration approved tests for COVID-19

Opening. Allows municipalities to expedite changes to their zoning rules or other ordinances to expand outdoor dining; Creates an expedited approval process for restaurants and other establishments that serve food to get fast-tracked permission to create or expand outdoor dining areas; Allows other businesses such as retail stores to get fast-tracked permission to sell goods on the sidewalk or in other outdoor areas, including shared spaces or spaces provided by municipalities.

Relief Fund. Authorization for OPM to direct DSS to provide Coronavirus Relief Fund distributions to nursing home facilities; Authorization for OPM to direct DSS to provide Coronavirus Relief Fund distributions to COVID recovery facilities and alternate COVID recovery facilities; Authorization for additional COVID-19 related hardship relief funding under the Coronavirus Relief Fund to nursing home facilities
Election. Procedures for local appointments and elections requiring in-person vote

Reopening Phase 1. Enforcement of sector rules governing the reopening of businesses; Extension of prohibition on large gatherings to June 20, 2020; Extension of restrictions on off-track betting, indoor fitness, and movie theaters to June 20;
Further clarification of limits on restaurants, bars, and private clubs – mixed drinks permitted for takeout delivery.
Election. Modifications to permit the use of absentee ballots to reduce the risk of COVID-19 transmission during August 11, 2020 primary;

Opening. Reopening of barbershops and hair salons on June 1; 
Amended prohibitions on large gatherings.
Healthcare. Mandatory COVID-19 testing for staff of private and municipal nursing homes, residential communities and assisted living agencies.

Restriciotn Modifications. Modification of safety rules for drive-in religious gatherings; Safety rules for drive-in graduations; Suspension of the involuntary discharge of nursing facility residents and residential care home residents who may be discharged to homeless shelters, except during emergency situations or with respect to COVID-19 recovered discharges.

Modifications. Modify limitation on group sizes in child care; Waiver of requirement to hold annual agricultural fair and reporting requirement to maintain agricultural society property tax exemption; Mandatory COVID-19 testing for staff of private and municipal nursing home facilities, managed residential communities, and assisted living services agencies
Travel. Safety advisory regarding travel from states with high infection rates.
Renting. Extended protections for residential renters affected by COVID-19.
Relief Funds. Authorization for DSS to provide funding from the Coronavirus Relief Fund to additional providers.
Modifications. Modifying minimum service hours for private non-medical institutions for adults.

Renting. Authorization for temporary rental housing program;
Temporary mortgage relief program.

Ease of Restrictions. Repeal of advisory self-quarantine; 
Travel. Mandatory self-quarantine for travelers from states with high COVID-19 infection levels
Ease of Restrictions. Modifications to face covering requirements;  Permission for DECD commissioner to establish size limits for private gatherings.

Ease of Restrictions. Extension of expanded outdoor dining; 
Renting. Modification of the extension of 30-day period of credit for liquor permittees; Extension of eviction moratorium.
Schools. Schools reopened for the first time since they were closed in March. Less than one-third reopenned for fully in-person learning.

Restrictions. Reissuance and extension of COVID-19 executive orders to November 9, 2020; Extension of agency and municipality orders of concurrent duration with public health and civil preparedness emergencies
Restricitons. Amendments to mandatory self-quarantine for travelers from states with high COVID-19 levels; Authorization for the issuance of fines.
Reopening. Third of the reopennings allowed increased indoor capacity at businesses including restaurants and the limited indoor use of performing art venues.
Restricitons. Municipal authority to revert to the more restrictive pre-October 8, 2020 size and capacity limitations and rules for certain businesses and gatherings.
Travel. Amendments to mandatory self-quarantine for travelers from states with high COVID-19 levels.
Restrictions. Municipal authority to revert to more restrictive pre-October 8, 2020 size and capacity limitations and rules for certain businesses and gatherings.
Retreat from Opening. A retreat from the third phase of the reopneing and restrict restaurants and social gatherings, while also asking residents to remain home between 10 pm and 5 am.
Election. Election among the pandemic. Voters turned out in record numbers for the election despite the risks of the infection.

Return to Phase 2. Repeal of municipal authority and return to statewide protective measures; Reduced capacity at indoor graduation ceremonies; DECD authority to enact sector rules for youth sports; DECD authority to enact sector rules governing mandatory closing times for certain businesses and other establishments.
Orders. Extension of COVID-19 executive orders to February 9, 2021; Extension of agency and municipality orders of concurrent duration with public health and civil preparedness emergencies.
Enforcements. Additional enforcement authority regarding violations of size and capacity restrictions; Commissioner of Public Health measures to ensure enforcement.
Relief funds. Increase in weekly benefit amount and qualification for Lost Wages Assistance.
The first vaccination arrives. "It is the dawn of the new day". The Pfizer-BioNTech arrived and the first dose was administered at the Hartford Hospital.
Travel. Amendments to mandatory self-quarantine for travelers from states with high COVID-19 levels.
Hartford HealthCare employees were first group to receice the Moderna vaccine
$4 Billion in stimulus funds are heading to CT.

More than 100 nursing homes are on track to complete the first round of COVID-19 vaccinations by the end of the year, putting the state’s goal of completing the first round of vaccinations in all 213 facilities by the middle of January within reach.
Two cases of new, more contagious coronavirus strain discovered in Connecticut
